{"id":"quant-ph/0312013","submitter":"Henry Stapp","authors":"Henry P.Stapp","title":"Correspondence and analyticity","comments":"Invited contribution to a special issue of Publications of RIMS\n  commemorating the fortieth anniversary of the founding of the Research\n  Institute for Mathematical Science","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":"LBNL-53835","categories":"quant-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  The analyticity properties of the S matrix in the physical region are\ndetermined by the correspondence principle, which asserts that the predictions\nof classical physics are generated by taking the classical limit of the\npredictions of quantum theory. The analyticity properties deducible in this way\nfrom classical properties include the locations of the singularity surfaces,\nthe rules for analytic continuation around these surfaces, and the analytic\ncharacter (e.g., pole, logarithmic, etc.) of these singulatities. These\nimportant properties of the S matrix are thus derived without using stringent\nlocality assumptions. The quantum properties are derived by an analytic reverse\nengineering of the classical properties.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 1 Dec 2003 17:14:41 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
{"id":"quant-ph/0312014","submitter":"Jonathan A. Jones","authors":"M. S. Anwar, D. Blazina, H. Carteret, S. B. Duckett, T. K. Halstead,\n  J. A. Jones, C. M. Kozak and R. J. K. Taylor","title":"Preparing high purity initial states for nuclear magnetic resonance\n  quantum computing","comments":"4 pages including 2 figures. Changes from v.3 at request of referees.\n  Now in press at Physical Review Letters","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. Lett. 93, 040501 (2004)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevLett.93.040501","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  Here we demonstrate how para-hydrogen can be used to prepare a two-spin\nsystem in an almost pure state which is suitable for implementing nuclear\nmagnetic resonance (NMR) quantum computation. A 12ns laser pulse is used to\ninitiate a chemical reaction involving pure para-hydrogn (the nuclear spin\nsinglet of H2). The product, formed on the microsecond timescale, contains a\nhydrogen derived two-spin system with an effective spin-state purity of 0.916.\nTo achieve a comparable result by direct cooling would require an unmanageable\n(in the liquid state) effective spin temperature of 6.4mK or an impractical\nmagnetic field of 0.45MT at room temperature. The resulting spin state has an\nentanglement of formation of 0.822 and cannot be described by local hidden\nvariable models.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 1 Dec 2003 17:26:34 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 23 Jan 2004 17:43:21 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Mon, 9 Feb 2004 12:00:20 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Wed, 26 May 2004 09:46:58 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
